# Plain-language meticulous

You don't have to write symbols. Meticulous understands arguments written
the way you'd say them — a sentence per premise, "Therefore" for the
conclusion. Each one below is checked, its form named, its proof found.

If P, then Q. P. Therefore, Q.

If P, then Q. Not Q. Therefore, not P.

If P, then Q. If Q, then R. Therefore, if P, then R.

Either P or Q. Not P. Therefore, Q.

# Categorical arguments

Words like "all", "no", and "some" become quantifiers. Use the same term
throughout (say "mortal" both times, not "mortal" then "mortals").

All men are mortal. Socrates is a man. Therefore, Socrates is mortal.

Some men are philosophers. All philosophers are wise. Therefore, some men are wise.

# The four categorical forms

You can also name a claim in prose and inspect it on its own:

claim A : All men are mortal
claim E : No men are mortal
claim I : Some men are mortal
claim O : Some men are not mortal

# Claims and checks work in prose too

check (If P, then Q) equivalent (not P or Q)
